segments.text: So the first question is, do you think the astronauts are heroes?
I think that heroes is something that people make up in their minds.
You'll find that most people that get put in the image of heroes are just plain people like anybody else, and they've all got their quirks and their weaknesses and their strong points.
I had heroes when I was growing up, and they included guys like Chuck Yeager, who I later
learned to know personally and found out that Chuck, he is quite a man.
He's still a hero of mine, but he's still a person.
I think that astronauts get put in that position.
And consequently, they should be aware of it because they do have a strong influence on how kids think of them and pattern their lives.
How do you feel about the media blitzes that you received as an astronaut?
Well, that comes and goes.
The media can be...
It can be an enemy.
It can be a friend.
Prior to flying the first flight of Columbia, we had a lot of criticism regarding the vehicle, were we ever going to get it airborne.
And after the flight, they were all our friends.
And I think as we fly more and more, they will tend to be more critical than they have been.
But they're going to start being that way.
And I think you just have to learn to deal with the media.
Quite often you learn after having been involved with some stories that they've done that they can slant things, maybe not on purpose, but they just don't know all the facts.
So the way it comes out in the newspaper quite often is not the way it really is.
What kind of pressures has being an astronaut placed on your family?
The main thing, I think, is that I'm going a lot.
But since I'm a Navy man and have spent months on cruises, I think at least my wife
grew accustomed to that.
So I believe they're more or less comfortable with the thing.
I think perhaps during the flight and some of the hullabaloo that was associated with that, both pre and post, perhaps my kids got a little bit more of that.
And they enjoyed it.
I think it was kind of like being in the spotlight.
But I believe they've adapted to it fairly well.
How long will it be before we see women and minorities in space?
Well.
I'm a Southpaw.
I got to fly that.
We're one of the last minorities left around.
I think that we have eight ladies training to fly right now.
Not training to fly, but in the astronaut office.
And we have three blacks.
And we also, correction, we've got four.
We've got four blacks.
Hey, Chuck.
Hey, Chuck.
How are you?
One Hispanic.
Yes, sir.
Check, please.
oriental origin who mixes quite a few things.
And I think that there's chances of seeing some of those people fly as early as next year.
Are you going to say the lowest damage to any hero image that there might be?
No, I don't think so.
The First Lady and the First Black that end up flying, I know, are going to have more hero image associated with them than most of us have in the past.
I almost feel sorry for them.
That's really going to be a tough load to carry.
Are the astronauts stamped out of the same mold physically or mentally?
Oh, no.
We've got, I believe, 78 people in the astronaut office now, currently, and quite a few that have gone on to retire.
And you'll find out you've got just about as wide a range as individuals as you can find any place.
There's a certain amount of common
goal-oriented kind of philosophy, I believe, amongst the people.
And also you'll find that most of the people are very hard workers, tend to work long hours, be somewhat workaholics.
So there are some common threads, I believe, that link most of us, but there's still an awful lot of individualism.
What types of changes are being made for the women?
With regard to the spacecraft or how we operate?
Very little.
About the only thing is that the...

the waste management facility, the toilet, was designed to collect urine from either males or females, and that was a minor modification that you probably wouldn't even know if I pointed it out to you.
And other than that, size-wise, the pressure suit that would go outside has had to come down in a smaller size.
That really is about all.
We've found that working in space is a very relaxing, easy kind of an environment, with the exception of going outside in the pressure suit.
And so there's not really any strength involved with it.
And some of these ladies that we've got, for example, are awful smart.
They're a lot smarter than some of the guys we've got around here.
So as far as brains, they've got it all.
We really haven't had to make any modifications for them, except maybe in our mentalities.
Yeah.
What is the criteria for becoming an astronaut?
Well, there's a set standard of things people have to have
filled, you know, degrees.
We're looking for people with degrees in science or engineering.
We've got two categories we selected now, pilot and mission specialist.
Pilot type, of course, has to have quite a bit of time in high-performance jet airplanes.
The mission specialists are mainly looking for people with usually PhDs, but all that's really required to apply is a master's.

You look for people that like to do diverse things, that are interested in learning all about the way things operate, that tend to be operational in nature rather than all people that want to go do experiments.
We have a lot of people with scientific backgrounds,
You're really the kind of person we need.
It's not somebody that wants to go down and do detailed science, but somebody that likes to study the overall thing.
Are the astronauts fairly socially close-knit?
Not really.
I think the initial astronauts that came down, smaller groups and so forth, tended to be a little bit closer-knit group than what we've got now.
We have small groups that are friends and tend to socialize, but not as a big unit.
We have periodic parties.
Most of them are associated with celebrating after a flight.
We'll probably have one just a little...
Jack and Gordo that just got down from STS-3 will pull off here in the next week or so.
But we really don't tend to socialize as a group all that much.
Is there anything like an Astronaut's Wives Club?
Used to be a long time ago, but most of the wives just weren't interested in that sort of thing.
And some of the wives will still get together for coffee periodically, but there's not anything like a wives club.
Do you see the effects of public opinion in that?
We see the effects of public opinion mainly through our budget.
And I guess right now it would appear that the public is really behind us, at least you can see that reflected in Congress.
Congress is very much in favor of what we're doing.
And I think that's mainly been the case all along, although
When we're not in the public eye, it is hard for the public to voice that support.
But with the flights that we've got going with the space shuttle now, all we're hearing are positive words.
You'll hear a few negative people, but they are not the majority.
Is NASA suffering from the recent budget cuts?
Very little compared to most of the agencies NASA fared out very well.
Now, we did get some of our unmanned science projects cut back, unfortunately.
We hope those will mainly just be deferred, and then we'll get to carry them out eventually.
But in the long term, NASA fared very well in that, and that is because
of both Congress and administration being very pro-space right now.
Is the Defense Department in any way blowing up now?
I think it is primarily due to the Defense Department's commitment to the space shuttle that we were able to fare those couple of years that we had prior to getting the shuttle off.
We were having so much problems with our main engines, our tiles, our thermal protection system, that if we had not had the Department of Defense support
we would have had a tough time holding our own.
But we have had it, and I think it's been good for the space program.
There's still been some people concerned about the shuttle's association with the military and that the science civilian end will end up suffering.
I don't think that's going to be the case.
The military has always utilized space just about ever since the first satellite going up, and they're going to continue to doing that.
The space shuttle is just going to have a way of getting those satellites up easier and cheaper than we've been doing with unmanned rockets.
And so I think it's good that we're working with the military.
Now, I'm a little bit biased since I'm a military person myself.
OK, plaque was placed on the moon.
It said, here men came from the planet Earth, first set foot upon the moon July of 1969 AD.
We came in peace for all of mankind.
Are we still in space for peaceful reasons?
Absolutely.

The United States is committed to a space treaty that says we'll only use space for peaceful purposes, and I actually think it's been the military use of space, both in this country and in the Soviet Union, that has helped us maintain peace over at least the past decade.
The nature of trying to maintain treaties like SALT
without a valid means of ensuring what the other country is doing is just not reasonable.
And you can use detection means from space to ensure that all signers of the treaties are doing what they say they're doing.
And I think that has been one of the big reasons that we've been able to avoid any open confrontation with the Soviet Union.
And so for that reason, I really think that we ought to continue to use space.
So you feel this type of space diplomacy works?
Absolutely.
It beats anything else anybody else has come up with.
Do you feel that space will turn into the next location for an arms building?
It is possible.
It is possible, certainly.
And I hope that is not the case.
But it's an environment that certainly has to be inviting for anybody worrying about...
the kind of weapons we now have on the Earth.
It's a new environment that man has tended to utilize each environment it is found to conduct war with.
So it's going to take some very strong-minded people and countries to keep that from happening.
And I think that is the intent of the US to try to keep weapons out of space.
It often depends on what the other guy does.
So then you feel that space-based wars are possible?
Certainly possible.
But right now, anything is possible.
Right now, it does not appear that we're necessarily heading in that direction.
So then would you say that they're inevitable?
No, I would not say they're inevitable.
I think we can control it.
I'll tell you.
What do you see as our future in space?
Well, in near term, it's fairly easy to see.
We're building a total of four orbiters or space shuttles.
Hopefully, maybe even getting a fifth, and then maybe even subsequent ones.
We'll be flying many flights each year, upwards, hopefully, of 20 some odd.
By putting those many flights up, then you're going to see lots more of the same kind of satellites that we have now, more sophisticated ones.
And hopefully those will be used to enhance the quality of life we have here on Earth.
Eventually we would like to see us move out and build a permanent orbiting space station.
And that is the next logical step in our progression of exploration of space.
That is probably going to take close to 10 years from the time we're given the go-ahead on it, and we have not been given a go-ahead, although we're pursuing that pretty heavily at NASA.
So I think that's the next big step you'll see in space.
Beyond that, with that space station, we'll be going back to the moon, building a colony so that we can stay there and explore it for longer periods of time.
We'll eventually go to Mars and beyond.
But those kinds of things, in my mind, are...
They will happen, but it's impossible to say when.
People in these United States tend to be reactioners.
I guess we'll have to wait until somebody does something to prod us into making us want to do that.
I'll see you in May.
What do you see as the legacy of space?
Well, I'm not sure it's ready to have left a legacy yet.
I think it's more like still a dream.
We've only scratched the surface of what can be done in space.
Since the first Sputnik was up and Yuri Gagarin and Al Shepard made their flights, we've come a long ways.
I was back in college when that happened, about your age.
And the things that have happened in that
what to me seems like a fairly short span of time, are fairly fantastic.
But we're still just kind of learning how to crawl.
We're not up and running yet.
Do you feel that all the money we spent on the space programs and the various different programs within could have been better spent elsewhere?
Well, there's always going to be speculation about hindsight.
Could I have done this better?
Could I have done that better?
I think perhaps, especially back in the Apollo days, we could have been more efficient with them that way we were spending our money.

We had as a goal to go to the moon in the 60s, and we used money to help solve a lot of problems, to get over hurdles that we could have probably solved more efficiently with less funds if we had elected to spread out the time it would take.
We have, since that time, with the shuttle, we have started to work in a way that is a lot more efficient and giving the taxpayer, I feel, more product for his money.

The returns on going into space are multifold, and people have talked about spinoffs and all that kind of stuff, what it's done for medicine computers, and you can get spiels and see books written on the subject.
Those monies, I think it's also important to note that
They weren't just burned up in the flames of the rocket as it shot off.

Those go into the American workers' pockets as wages, and so it is not necessarily a welfare program, but it certainly stimulates the economy in a certain way, and it gives us a positive, tangible kind of a...
return on doing it.

So I think one of the things that I learned after our flight that there was also maybe an even more important product of the flight, and that is the American people really need something that they can grab hold of and say, we did that and I'm proud of it.
They certainly felt that way about the space shuttle.
I think they still do.
And all of those things, to me, add up as far as the government spending.
I don't think for the amount of money that we're spending on the space program, you could have gotten very much good out of those monies invested in other places.
People use the term, I forget the exact specifics, but...
health, education, welfare kind of things, agencies, they go through NASA's, the same amount of NASA's total year budget, they go through that in like a week.
And you could have given them another week's budget, and the good that they would have been able to do with it is very small compared to what I think we've been able to produce.
So you feel the space programs helped unify the Americans?
It certainly did right after, I know it did when we went to the moon.
It did...
with the first flight of the shuttle.
And maybe we were needing something.
We'd had a lot of things with the hostages and Iran.
few things like that that went on that we were getting to wonder if we were still the great country that we are.
At least a lot of people were, and the flight really did help solidify at least some patriotism and national pride again.
And that'll come up.
We'll do something else down the road that they'll show the same amount of pride in.
How, in your opinion, did the war in Vietnam affect the space program and vice versa?
It tended to...
divert attention and funds away from it primarily because our national goals were oriented elsewhere.
And I think that's natural when you're involved in a conflict.
That's where our money should be going to try to resolve that.
The space program survived all that and came out maybe the better for it because that was part of the role I was talking about earlier.
We learned as an agency here at NASA
to work much more efficiently and not tend to go solve all of our problems with pouring more dollars into them, but sell them otherwise.
Being in orbit in space, if you will,
In looking back, you can see the Earth and you see the space.
How does this expanse of space affect you?
It's kind of mind-boggling at first, the fact that you can see as much with just a glance as compared to what we're normally used to.
It certainly gives one a feeling of...
a newness, a unique environment that you're working in.
Space is really a black place.
Boy, I'm telling you, if you're not night adapted, when you look out into the black, that is about as black as anything could be.
But it's also a beautiful sight, looking at the Earth from that altitude, or the kind of altitude we're talking about, the low Earth orbit, which we were about 170 statute miles up.
And the speed, you know, you go around the Earth once every hour and a half, so you know you're really moving on.
But...
But you're just floating around while you're doing it.
So I don't know of anything to liken it to.
But it is really a pleasurable kind of a treat to enjoy.
Do you feel space will become commercial?
Oh, yes, in fact, it already has.

Of the satellites that the space shuttle is carrying, about a third of them are commercial satellites, primarily in the areas of communications, but communications, weather, and that sort of thing are utilizing space extensively and have been, you know, when you tune in to the evening news and you see the...
The weather shot, what all the weather is, part of that is from commercial satellites.
You can sit down and you can watch a sports event that's going on in Europe or a news event that's taking place in South America or something.
Most of those are all due to commercial satellites.
We're also going to learn to do things like make new products up there that you can't make as well down here on Earth due to gravity.
We experimented a little bit with one on this flight.
It's a process called electrophoresis, which is used to generate certain kinds of pharmaceuticals.
And the next flight will also have sort of a small factory for doing that that some commercial enterprises are interested in.
Personally, is it worth it?
Oh, yeah.
The investment of the time that I personally put into it, absolutely.
Well, I actually was associated with the space program
that the Department of Defense was doing as early as 1966.
I was supposed to have flown on that, and it got canceled, and I was transferred here to NASA in 69.
And it was 81 before I got to fly, but had a great deal of fun in the meantime.
I enjoyed every minute of it and thought I was able to contribute something rather positive to the flights that we did throughout the 70s.
The treat of actually getting to fly was well worth it, and I hope to do it six, eight, ten more times if they'll let me.
And for the country?
Oh, absolutely.
Well, I've gone into several of the regions for the country that I thought that it was productive, but to me...
If a country is going to maintain its greatness like this one has, it needs to push the frontiers of technology.
And the space program has given us an excellent way of doing that.
You can't just sit back and write on your laurels.
You've got to keep pushing and looking for new things and exploiting different kinds of science that we haven't utilized before.
If you don't, we're going to be left behind.
And I think the space program has given us a good forum for doing that.
What do you personally think of the men who've used their space careers as stepping stones to political ends?
All the more power to them.
You know, people get through the space program and have left it for various reasons, quite a few of them because the flights were so far in between.
And...
As I said earlier, we've got people of all kinds of personalities and what have you, and some of them are very...
It would seem the natural thing for them to do to get into politics.
I think the fact that they were astronauts maybe is that gave them a little bit of push that I don't see anything wrong with that.
Most people that get into politics, they'll use anything in their background that's a plus to help them.
I don't think...
The fact that they were astronauts really made them better politicians or better in government, but I believe it did probably widen their background a little bit.
All right.
Okay.
